docs.abstract: President Trump, who has vowed to the N.R.A. that “I will never, ever let you down,” seems likely to keep that promise given his bond with gun owners and their culture.
docs.snippet: President Trump, who has vowed to the N.R.A. that “I will never, ever let you down,” seems likely to keep that promise given his bond with gun owners and their culture.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s staff tried to be reassuring. Stop focusing, they told jittery allies, on the sound bites from the White House Cabinet Room earlier this week when Mr. Trump appeared to embrace longstanding conservative taboos like gun confiscation and comprehensive background checks.

headline.main: After Brief Split, Trump and N.R.A. Appear to Reconcile
headline.print_headline: After Brief Rift, the President and the N.R.A. Appear to Be in Sync Again

docs.abstract: The Trump administration has been surprisingly frank in saying it wants to use the courts to curb the power of federal agencies, a longstanding goal of conservatives.
docs.snippet: The Trump administration has been surprisingly frank in saying it wants to use the courts to curb the power of federal agencies, a longstanding goal of conservatives.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — It has been practically a given that anyone nominated for a federal judgeship by a Republican president had to pass an unspoken litmus test — usually on abortion but often on any number of divisive social issues.

headline.main: Trump’s New Judicial Litmus Test: Shrinking ‘the Administrative State’
headline.print_headline: New Litmus Test for Trump’s Court Picks: Taming the Bureaucracy

docs.abstract: President Trump turned his attention to the midterm battle that awaits Republicans here: Minnesota is one of the most important states in the fight for control of Congress.
docs.snippet: President Trump turned his attention to the midterm battle that awaits Republicans here: Minnesota is one of the most important states in the fight for control of Congress.
docs.lead_paragraph: DULUTH, Minn. — Shortly after caving to political pressure and signing an executive order that ends the separation of families by detaining parents and children together at the border, President Trump vowed at a rally here on Wednesday that his administration would be “just as tough” on immigration as before.

headline.main: ‘We’re Sending Them the Hell Back,’ Trump Says of Securing the Country’s Borders
headline.print_headline: Trump Brings Bombast to Minnesota With Eye on Midterms and Beyond

docs.abstract: The attorney general reversed an immigration appeals court decision granting asylum to a Salvadoran woman whose husband had sexually and physically abused her.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Attorney General Jeff Sessions on Monday made it all but impossible for asylum seekers to gain entry into the United States by citing fears of domestic abuse or gang violence, in a ruling that could have a broad effect on the flow of migrants from Central America.

headline.main: Sessions Says Domestic and Gang Violence Are Not Grounds for Asylum

docs.abstract: The Democratic Party skirted disaster in California and lined up likely gains in New Jersey, but Republicans saw some bright signs as well.
docs.snippet: The Democratic Party skirted disaster in California and lined up likely gains in New Jersey, but Republicans saw some bright signs as well.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Democrats enhanced their prospects for winning control of the House with Tuesday’s coast-to-coast primary results, skirting potential calamity in California and lining up likely gains in New Jersey and possible victories in Iowa and New Mexico.

headline.main: Democrats Strengthen House Takeover Prospects in Primary Voting
headline.print_headline: Voting Shores Up Democrats’ Push To Retake House

docs.abstract: The Veterans Affairs Department, which has been working to streamline private care, is frozen and bleeding talent amid a leadership vacuum in Washington.
docs.snippet: The Veterans Affairs Department, which has been working to streamline private care, is frozen and bleeding talent amid a leadership vacuum in Washington.
docs.lead_paragraph: At first, it was one doctor quitting the tiny Ukiah Veterans Affairs Outpatient Clinic in Northern California. Then another left, and another, until of the five doctors there a year ago, only one remained.

headline.print_headline: Void in Leadership Atop Veterans Affairs Leads to Chaos Below
